where do you personally host bots, sorry if inappropriate question but just wanted some insight
Cryptð•†ð•¨ð•â„‚ð•šð•¥ð•ªð•„â„™ðŸ› 2024-10-12 3:37 AM
if you're cheap you can buy a raspberry pi for like $20-$50 and host it at home, the power to keep it operating isn't big and you're already (assuming) paying for the internet already. obviously shit fails it's you to troubleshoot (power loss, internet loss etc) a vps (virtual private server) is also an alternative, some costing few bucks a month (depending how you can pay, where you live, where you want it hosted etc). the upside is its more reliable. there's one free vps option called Oracle, but it has been blocked where i live (sanctions). amazon, googleand Microsoft i think also offers free stuff, but i believe it's only 1 year. lastly, as my friend did it because he's new to all of this and just runs it when his windows computer is on. not efficient. ps, theres an episode in a tech tv show where a small startup asks a friend who works at a uni to let them host a server in a uni. so if you have connections maybe that can be arranged. (edited)
3:39 AM
for a discord bot, the power/performance requirement isn't big. some more demanding tasks might include audio playback and processing some large amount of texts (like those chat charts that are pinned) (edited)
3:44 AM
managing a red bot (babu is basically a "clone") is very simple and requires minimal tech knowledge as the instructions are as simple as it could be.
3:45 AM
we have tech peep here so we can "afford" those bots, but honestly for a day to day task, dyno bot is more than enough, plus a couple of bots that does games
